{"questionId":"17631","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The Maxwell Ohm Company is designing a portable Bluetooth speaker. The speaker is in the&nbsp;shape of a cylinder with a hemisphere at each end of the cylinder.</p>\n<p><img style=\"display:block;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto;\" src=\"__IMG__/dbcd221b4bb4d9c012b7a806f9934266848ede94.png\"></p>\n<p>The dimensions of the speaker, in centimetres, are illustrated in the following diagram where <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>r</mi></math>&nbsp;is the radius of the hemisphere, and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>l</mi></math> is the length of the cylinder, with <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>r</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>0</mn></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>l</mi><mo>≥</mo><mn>0</mn></math>.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/d80c74eb2795a9d1751de44a78ed4859ee9616d8.png\"></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The Maxwell Ohm Company has decided that the speaker will have a surface area of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>300</mn><mo> </mo><msup><mtext>cm</mtext><mn>2</mn></msup></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The quality of sound from the speaker will improve as <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>V</mi></math> increases.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Calculate the maximum value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>V</mi></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>V</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>150</mn><mfenced><msqrt><mfrac><mn>75</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi></mfrac></msqrt></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><msup><mfenced><msqrt><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mn>75</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi></mfrac></mstyle></msqrt></mfenced><mn>3</mn></msup></mrow><mn>3</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp; <em><strong>OR</strong></em>&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>V</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><msup><mfenced><msqrt><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mn>75</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi></mfrac></mstyle></msqrt></mfenced><mn>3</mn></msup></mrow><mn>3</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Award <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em> for correct substitution in the formula for the volume of the speaker or the volume of a sphere.</p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>489</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>488</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>602</mn><mo>…</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>100</mn><msqrt><mfrac><mn>75</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi></mfrac></msqrt></mrow></mfenced><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><msup><mtext>cm</mtext><mn>3</mn></msup></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(A1)(G2)</strong></em></p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Accept <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>489</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>795</mn><mo>…</mo></math> from use of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn></math> sf value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msqrt><mfrac><mn>75</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi></mfrac></msqrt></math>.&nbsp;Award <strong><em>(M1)(A1)</em>(ft)</strong> for correct substitution in their volume of speaker. Follow through from parts (a) and (f).</p>\n<p><em><strong>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"17631","referenceCode":"19N.2.SL.TZ0.T_6g","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Calculate the maximum value of V.","paper":"2","level":"SL","questionNumber":"g","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","Topic 5—Calculus","Topic 5—Calculus","SL 5.3—Differentiating polynomials, n E Z","Topic 5—Calculus","SL 5.6—Stationary points, local max and min","Topic 5—Calculus","SL 5.7—Optimisation","Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","SL 3.1—3d space, volume, angles, midpoints"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}